#### Location of weather station with highest elevation

```{r}
library(leaflet)
leaflet(elev) %>%
  addProviderTiles('OpenStreetMap') %>% 
  addCircles(lat=~lat,lng=~lon, opacity=1, fillOpacity=1, radius=100)
```

#### Time series of temperature and wind speed

```{r}
library(lubridate)
elev$date <- with(elev, ymd_h(paste(year, month, day, hour, sep= ' ')))
summary(elev$date)
elev <- elev[order(elev$date), ]
head(elev)

plot(elev$date, elev$temp, type='l')
plot(elev$date, elev$wind.sp, type='l')
```

### 8 - Asking questions

**What does each quality control variable (e.g., temp.qc, wind.sp.qc) actually represent?**

-   `wind.dir.qc` : indicates ISD's[^2] evaluation of the quality status of the wind direction
-   `wind.sp.qc` : indicates ISD’s evaluation of the quality status of the wind gust/speed
-   `temp.qc` : indicates ISD’s evaluation of the quality status of the hourly temperature average

[^2]: ISD = Federal Climate Complex Data Documentation for Integrated Surface Data

All quality control variable names used the same values for passing, failing, or missing the quality control checks:

-   1 = passed
-   3 = failed
-   9 = missing
